1. Introduction¶

This report intends to provide information about the air bombings carried out by the allied forces during the second world war. For this purpose, data provided by the Theater History of Operations Reports, a compilation of records declassified by the United States Department of Defense, was used.

Data Wrangling and cleaning¶

The first thing that we can observe is that our dataset have a total of nineteen (19) columns. Most of the column names are self explanatory, but there are some like MSNDATE (mission date), NAF (numbered airforce responsible for mission), AC_ATTACKING (number of aircraft), TONS_HE (high-explosives), TONS_IC (incendiary devices), TONS_FRAG (fragmentation bombs) that we will rename for better readbility. Also there are many columns that have missing data, we will fill these missing values with a "non avaliable" value.

3 Data Analysis¶

3.1 Number of aircrafts vs the tons of munitions dropped¶

First of all we want to do a quick analysis of the number of aircrafts that participated in the missions and the tons of munitions dropped. Since the 178281 records will slow and obscure the visualization we will use a sample of 10000 random records and create a scatterplot to better identify the relation between this two variables.

From this scatterplot we can see that there is a positive correlation between the number of aircrafts and the tons of munitions dropped. It is important to note that the number of aircrafts is not the number of aircrafts that dropped munitions, but the number of aircrafts that participated in the mission. This means that the number of aircrafts that dropped munitions is probably lower than the number of aircrafts that participated.

3.2 Munitions dropped by allied countries¶

Next we will address the tons of aerial munnitions dropped by country. For this, we will visualize it via a bar chart to display the differences by country. To get a better grasp of the numbers, we will convert the tons of munition to kilotons.

From this chart we can see that the United States was the country that dropped the most munitions, followed by Great Britain. The rest of the countries dropped less than 1 kiloton of munitions.

3.2.1 Types of munnitons dropped by the United States and Great Britain¶

Since the United States and Great Britain were the countries that dropped the most munnitions, we will focus on them and see what type of munnitions they dropped. For this we will use a stacked bar chart to visualize the different types of munnitions dropped by the United States and Great Britain.

As we can see, most of the munitions dropped by both countries were the "high explosive" type, followed by a large margin by incendiary bombs. Great Britain dropped almost no Fragmentation explosives (1208).

3.3 Bombing operations over time¶

Next we will explore the use of incendiary and fragmentation explosives by analyzing if there is a trend between the use of these over time against the total munitions dropped.

3.3.1 Bombs dropped over time in the Pacific Threater of Operations¶

We will take a closer look at the bombings in the Pacific Threater of Operations during 1944 and 1945 to assess some trends with the use of fragmentation and incendiary explosives. We will sample our data with a frequency of a one month interval to better visualize these trends.

A few patterns emerge in the PTO data. First we see a very clear escalation of overall bombings leading up to febraury, 19 1945 (The invasion of Iwo Jima). Incendiary munitions show three spikes and confirm that the fourth spike seen in the preceding example was directed at the bombing of Japan after Germany’s surrender. Lastly we can see that the abrupt descent of the bombings correspond to the surrender of Japan in August 15, 1945. For this reason both date are highlighted in the chart.
